<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>CSIR PYQ Unit III Q4 — Q as Z-module</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[As a \(\mathbb{Z}\)-module, \(\mathbb{Q}\) (the rationals) is:]]></text>
  </questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: Injective but not projective.</strong><br>\(\mathbb{Q}\) is divisible as a \(\mathbb{Z}\)-module (for every \(x\in\mathbb{Q}\) and \(n\ne 0\), there exists \(y=x/n\in\mathbb{Q}\) with \(ny=x\)). Divisible \(\mathbb{Z}\)-modules are injective. \(\mathbb{Q}\) is not projective over \(\mathbb{Z}\) because projective \(\mathbb{Z}\)-modules are free, and \(\mathbb{Q}\) is not free (it has no basis as a \(\mathbb{Z}\)-module).</p>]]></text>
  </generalfeedback>
