<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>CSIR PYQ Unit III Q9 — Cayley–Hamilton theorem</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[The Cayley–Hamilton theorem states that for any square matrix \(A\) over a commutative ring with characteristic polynomial \(p(\lambda)\):]]></text>
  </questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: \(p(A)=0\).</strong><br>Every matrix satisfies its own characteristic polynomial. If \(p(\lambda)=\det(\lambda I-A)\), then \(p(A)=0\). This follows from the structure of finitely generated modules over PIDs applied to \(F[x]\) acting on \(F^n\) via \(T\) (i.e., \(F[x]\)-module structure on \(F^n\)).</p>]]></text>
  </generalfeedback>
